title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington Rand 1911
postcontent: This is a conversation piece: a 1944 GI pistol that was decommissioned, and then was re-assembled and registered with the BATF by the enterprising gunsmith who took this project on. I’ve had some 1911 experts look at it, and have been told that the slide is a type 2 Remington Rand slide, the magazine is correct for the period, and the frame appears to have been decommissioned by the military and then re-manufactured, certified safe and issued a new serial number by the BATF. It was then purchased from a specialty gun shop in Idaho in the early nineties. You can see a faint line next to the serial number in the last of the pictures where the frame was welded, and you can see a shiny spot on the L hand side of the slide in the first picture where the frame and slide aren't perfectly aligned.I have shot this pistol, to see how/if it would fire: it does indeed fire, cycles just fine, and is accurate. Spent cases are slightly ballooned near the base, however. Pics have been added of spent rounds. Own a piece of history: $450. Please, no lowball offers. Happy to work a trade for a Glock 43.

The Sig Sauer® P290 RS EDC (Every Day Carry) is an extremely reliable and concealable semi-auto pistol that offers the ballistic advantage of the battle-proven 9mm cartridge. The pistol operates with a locked-breech, short recoil action (instead of blowback) that locks the action closed. Slide serrations enhance the shooter's ability to pull the slide back for loading and clearing the action. The P290 RS also has restrike capabilities in the case a cartridge does not fire the shooter simply has to pull the trigger again. Textured and replaceable grip panels, and textured front and back straps provide a non-slip grip for enhanced fire control. The Sig Sauer P290 RS EDC Semi-Auto Pistol comes with contrast sights, dovetailed to the slide.
